🧠 1. Functional Requirements (WHAT system should do)

These are user-facing features:

✅ Core Features
User Authentication
Register / Login (email/phone)
1:1 Messaging
Send/receive messages between two users
Group Messaging
Create groups
Add/remove users
Send messages in group
Text + Media Messages
Support:
Text
Images
Videos
Files
Message History
Store past messages
Pagination / lazy loading
Delivery & Read Receipts
Sent ✓
Delivered ✓✓
Read ✓✓ (blue)
⚡ 2. Non-Functional Requirements (HOW system should behave)

These are system qualities (very important in interviews):

🚀 Scale
~1 Billion users
~100 messages/user/day
👉 ≈ 100 Billion messages/day
⚖️ CAP Theorem
Prioritize:
👉 Availability > Consistency

💡 Why?

Chat apps should not go down
Slight delay in message sync is acceptable
⚡ Low Latency
Message delivery < 300ms
🛡️ Reliability
No message loss
Guaranteed delivery (retry + queue)
🧱 3. Core Entities (Data Model)

These are your main database objects:

👤 User
{
  userId,
  name,
  phone/email,
  status
}
👥 Group
{
  groupId,
  members: [userIds],
  createdAt
}
💬 Message / Chat
{
  messageId,
  senderId,
  chatId,
  content,
  type: "text | media",
  timestamp,
  status
}
🔌 4. API Design (VERY IMPORTANT)

Split into HTTP APIs + WebSocket APIs

🧾 4.1 User APIs
POST /v1/user/register
POST /v1/user/login
💬 4.2 One-to-One Chat APIs
🔹 Send Message (Real-time)
WS: /v1/messages/send

👉 Uses WebSocket (low latency)

🔹 Get Chat History
GET /v1/chat/{userId}
Pagination supported
Returns message list
👥 4.3 Group APIs
Create Group
POST /v1/groups/create
Add Member
POST /v1/groups/{groupId}/add
Remove Member
POST /v1/groups/{groupId}/remove
Send Group Message
WS: /v1/messages/send
Get Group Messages
GET /v1/groups/{groupId}/messages

👉 Lazy loading / pagination

⚡ 5. Real-Time Communication (CRITICAL)
Use WebSockets
Client ↔ Server (persistent connection)
Flow:
1. User sends message
2. Goes via WebSocket
3. Server processes
4. Push to receiver instantly
🔄 6. Message Flow (End-to-End)
1. User types message
2. UI shows message (optimistic update)
3. Message sent via WebSocket
4. Server stores message
5. Server checks receiver:
   → Online → send instantly
   → Offline → store
6. Update status:
   sent → delivered → read
📦 7. Media Handling
Approach:
Upload file to storage (S3/CDN)
Get URL
Send URL in message

👉 Avoid sending large files via chat server

🧠 8. Performance Considerations (Frontend + System)
🔹 Pagination / Lazy Load
Load messages in chunks
🔹 Virtualization
Render only visible messages
🔹 Optimistic UI
Show message instantly before server response
🔹 Debouncing
Typing indicators
🔐 9. Reliability Mechanisms
✅ Message Queue
Prevent message loss
✅ Retry Logic
Resend failed messages
✅ Acknowledgements (ACK)
Confirm delivery
⚔️ 10. Key Design Decisions
🔹 WebSocket over HTTP
Real-time communication
🔹 Availability over Consistency
Better UX
🔹 Store-and-Forward Model
Works for offline users
🔥 Final Interview Summary (Use This)

“I would design a WhatsApp-like system with functional requirements like 1:1 and group messaging, media support, and message history. For non-functional requirements, I would ensure high scalability, low latency, and high availability. The system would use WebSockets for real-time communication, a store-and-forward model for offline users, and APIs for user and group management. Messages would be stored reliably with support for delivery and read receipts, and media would be handled via external storage.”

